Generating uniformly distributed random points along a curve¶

Ex. 1: Curve has a known function.¶

In [63]:
np.random.seed(547)

# Function and parameter range
def spiral(t):
    return np.array([np.exp(-.1*t)*np.cos(t), np.exp(-.1*t)*np.sin(t)])

domain = [0, 5*np.pi]

# Random points
x, t, s = r_arc(200, spiral, *domain, 50)

# Shape of spiral
shape_t = np.linspace(*domain, 500)
shape_x = spiral(shape_t)

# Set up plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8,8))
ax.set_xlim(-.85, 1.1)
ax.set_ylim(-.85, 1.1)

# Plot arc shape
ax.plot(*shape_x, color='gray', ls="--")

# Plot random data
ax.scatter(*x, marker='+', alpha=0.7, color='forestgreen')

# Total arc length
spiral_A = arc_length(spiral,*domain, 500)
ax.set_title('Total arc length: {}'.format(np.round(spiral_A, 3)), y=0.02, x=.97, loc='right')

plt.savefig('spiral.png')

Ex. 2: Curve in 3 dimensions, given by data points only.¶

Since the arc was given imprecisely, the arc has a blocky appearance, appearance, since arc was given imprecisely, but we can recover an organic shape by passing the kind='cubic' argument to r_arc_from_data().

np.random.seed(1172)

# Function and parameter range
def spiral2(t):
    return np.array([np.exp(-.1*t)*np.cos(t), np.exp(-.1*t)*np.sin(t), .004*t**2])

domain = [-2*np.pi, 10*np.pi]

# Pretend we were given a sequence of 40 points instead of the function
data_x = spiral2(np.linspace(*domain, 40))

# Random points
x, t, s = r_arc_from_data(200, None, data_x, kind='cubic')

# Set up plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.set_xlim(-2,2)
ax.set_ylim(-2,2)
ax.set_zlim(0,4)

ax.plot(*data_x, color='gray', ls="--")
ax.scatter(*x, marker='+', alpha=0.6, color='navy')

Generating uniformly distributed random points on a surface¶

Ex. 3: Surface as a function of two variables over square region.¶

In [65]:
np.random.seed(7643)

# Function and parameter region
def wave(t, u):
    return np.array([t, u, np.cos(t)*np.cos(u/1.4)])

domain_t = [0, 2*np.pi]
domain_u = [0, 2*np.pi]

# Get random points
x, t, u, St, Su = r_surface(3000, wave, *domain_t, *domain_u, 50,50)

# Set up plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0, wspace=0.1, bottom=.2)
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.view_init(30, 20)
ax.set_xlim(domain_t)
ax.set_ylim(domain_u)
ax.set_zlim(-np.pi, np.pi)

# Plot random points
ax.scatter(*x, marker='+', alpha=0.5, color='cornflowerblue')

# Plot the function itself
shape_t, shape_u = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(*domain_t, 25), np.linspace(*domain_u, 25))
shape_x = wave(shape_t, shape_u)
ax.plot_wireframe(*shape_x, color='black', ls="--", alpha = 0.3)

# Surface area
wave_A = surface_area(wave, *domain_t, *domain_u, 100, 100)
ax.set_title('Total surface area: {}'.format(np.round(wave_A, 3)), size=15, y=-0.05)

plt.savefig('wave.png')

Ex. 4: Parametric curve in two variables.¶

In [66]:
# Function and parameter region
def ellipsoid(t, u, a=6, b=4, c=8):
    return np.array([a*np.sin(u)*np.cos(t), b*np.sin(u)*np.sin(t), c*np.cos(u)])

domain_t = [0, 2*np.pi]
domain_u = [0, np.pi]

# Get random points
x, t, u, St, Su = r_surface(2000, ellipsoid, *domain_t, *domain_u, 20, 20)

# Set up plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0, wspace=0.1, bottom=.2)
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.set_xlim(-8.1, 8.1)
ax.set_ylim(-8.1, 8.1)
ax.set_zlim(-8.1, 8.1)

# Plot random points
ax.scatter(*x, marker='+', alpha=0.5, color='crimson')

# Plot function
shape_t, shape_u = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(*domain_t, 25), np.linspace(*domain_u, 25))
shape_x = ellipsoid(shape_t, shape_u)
ax.plot_wireframe(*shape_x, color='black', ls="--", alpha = 0.3)

# Surface area
ellipsoid_A = surface_area(ellipsoid, *domain_t, *domain_u, 100, 100)
ax.set_title('Total surface area: {}'.format(np.round(ellipsoid_A, 3)), size=15, y=-0.05)

Ex. 5: Points uniformly spaced along arc.¶

In [67]:
# Function and parameter range
def spiral3(t):
    return np.array([np.exp(-.1*t)*np.cos(t), 1.3*np.exp(-.2*t)*np.sin(t), 3.8-.0038*t**2])

domain = [-2*np.pi, 10*np.pi]

# Arc data
data_t = np.linspace(*domain, 400)
data_x = spiral3(data_t)

# Cumulation data
cum_s = arc_cumulator(data_t, data_x)[1]
L = cum_s[-1]

# Choose regularly spaced arc lengths and invert to parameter space
# This code matches source of r_arc_from_data()
points_s = np.linspace(0, L, 75)
points_t = interp1d(cum_s, data_t)(points_s)

# Evaluate function at received parameters
points_x = spiral3(points_t)

# Set up plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.set_xlim(-2,2)
ax.set_ylim(-1,3)
ax.set_zlim(0,4)
ax.set_title('Total arc length: {}'.format(np.round(L, 3)), size=15, y=-0.05)

# Plot arc shape
ax.plot(*data_x, color='gray', ls="--")

# Plot points
ax.scatter(*points_x, marker='+', alpha=1, color='purple')

Ex. 6: Points uniformly spaced over parametric surface.¶

Notice how point density decreases at the top of the spiral, where the area is narrower, so that the area of each “rectangle” is equal.

In [68]:
# Function and parameter region
def swoop(t, u):
    return np.array([u*np.exp(-.1*t)*np.cos(t), u*np.exp(-.1*t)*np.sin(t), 3.5*t/np.pi])

domain_t = [-2*np.pi, 5*np.pi]
domain_u = [4, 8]

# Surface data
data_t, data_u = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(*domain_t, 200), np.linspace(*domain_u, 10))
data_x = swoop(data_t, data_u)

# Cumulation data
cum_S_t, cum_S_u = surface_cumulator(data_t, data_u, data_x)[2:]
A = cum_S_t[-1]

# Choose regularly spaced intervals of area and invert to parameter space
# This code matches source of r_surface_from_data()
points_S_t, points_S_u = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(0,cum_S_t[-1],80),
                                     np.linspace(0,cum_S_u[-1],5))

# Evaluate the function over received parameters
points_t = interp1d(cum_S_t, data_t[0,:])(points_S_t)
points_u = interp1d(cum_S_u, data_u[:,0])(points_S_u)
points_x = swoop(points_t, points_u)

# Set up plot
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0, wspace=0.1, bottom=.2)
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
ax.set_xlim(-10, 15)
ax.set_ylim(-10, 15)
ax.set_zlim(-10, 15)
ax.set_title('Total surface area: {}'.format(np.round(A, 3)), size=15, y=-0.05)

# Plot function
ax.plot_surface(*data_x, color='black', ls="--", alpha=0.15)

# Plot points
ax.scatter(*points_x, marker='+', alpha=.7, color='forestgreen')
